[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] Integrating over all different values of *φ*(*x*) is equivalent to integrating over all Fourier modes, because taking a Fourier transform is a unitary linear transformation of field coordinates.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] When you change coordinates in a multidimensional integral by a linear transformation, the value of the new integral is given by the determinant of the transformation matrix.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] so that det *A* = ±1, and the sign depends on whether the rotation includes a reflection or not.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] The matrix that changes coordinates from *φ*(*x*) to *φ*(*k*) can be read off from the definition of a Fourier transform.
