[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] On a finite volume lattice, the determinant is nonzero and independent of the field values.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] and the path integral is a separate factor at each value of k.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] Each separate factor is an oscillatory Gaussian, and the width of the Gaussian diverges as the volume goes to infinity.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] In imaginary time, the *Euclidean action* becomes positive definite, and can be interpreted as a probability distribution.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] Since the probability of φk is a product, the value of φk at each separate value of k is independently Gaussian distributed.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] The variance of the Gaussian is ⁠1/*k*2*ddk*⁠, which is formally infinite, but that just means that the fluctuations are unbounded in infinite volume.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] In any finite volume, the integral is replaced by a discrete sum, and the variance of the integral is ⁠*V*/*k*2⁠.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] The path integral defines a probabilistic algorithm to generate a Euclidean scalar field configuration.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] Randomly pick the real and imaginary parts of each Fourier mode at wavenumber k to be a Gaussian random variable with variance ⁠1/*k*2⁠.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] This generates a configuration *φC*(*k*) at random, and the Fourier transform gives *φC*(*x*).
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] For real scalar fields, the algorithm must generate only one of each pair *φ*(*k*), *φ*(−*k*), and make the second the complex conjugate of the first.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] where |*C*| is the number of configurations, and the sum is of the product of the field values on each configuration.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] The Euclidean correlation function is just the same as the correlation function in statistics or statistical mechanics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] The quantum mechanical correlation functions are an analytic continuation of the Euclidean correlation functions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] For free fields with a quadratic action, the probability distribution is a high-dimensional Gaussian, and the statistical average is given by an explicit formula.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] But the Monte Carlo method also works well for bosonic interacting field theories where there is no closed form for the correlation functions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] Each mode is independently Gaussian distributed.
[src:quantum-field-theory/feynman-diagram] for *k* ≠ *k*′, since then the two Gaussian random variables are independent and both have zero mean.
