[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] and the equations of motion for f derived from extremizing the action S corresponding to L just set it equal to 1.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] In physics, such a quantity is "equal to 1 as an operator identity".
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] In mathematics, it "weakly converges to 1".
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] In either case, it is 1 in any expectation value, or when averaged over any interval, or for all practical purpose.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] This is called the Itō lemma in stochastic calculus, and the (euclideanized) canonical commutation relations in physics.
