[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] This integral has a rigorous mathematical interpretation as integration against the Wiener measure, denoted $\mu _{x}$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] The Wiener measure, constructed by Norbert Wiener gives a rigorous foundation to Einstein's mathematical model of Brownian motion.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] The subscript x indicates that the measure $\mu _{x}$ is supported on paths $\mathbf {x}$ with $\mathbf {x} (0)=x$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] Although the Wick-rotated Schrödinger equation does not have a direct physical meaning, interesting properties of the Schrödinger operator ${\hat {H}}$ can be extracted by studying it.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] Much of the study of quantum field theories from the path-integral perspective, in both the mathematics and physics literatures, is done in the Euclidean setting, that is, after a Wick rotation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] In particular, there are various results showing that if a Euclidean field theory with suitable properties can be constructed, one can then undo the Wick rotation to recover the physical, Lorentzian theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] On the other hand, it is much more difficult to give a meaning to path integrals (even Euclidean path integrals) in quantum field theory than in quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] is the action of the classical problem in which one investigates the path starting at time *t* = 0 and ending at time *t* = tf, and ${\mathcal {D}}\mathbf {x}$ denotes the integration measure over all paths.
