[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p01] Note, however, that the Euclidean path integral is actually in the form of a *classical* statistical mechanics model.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Both the Schrödinger and Heisenberg approaches to quantum mechanics single out time and are not in the spirit of relativity.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] for two simultaneous spatial positions x and y, and this is not a relativistically invariant concept.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The results of a calculation *are* covariant, but the symmetry is not apparent in intermediate stages.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] If naive field-theory calculations did not produce infinite answers in the continuum limit, this would not have been such a big problem – it would just have been a bad choice of coordinates.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] But the lack of symmetry means that the infinite quantities must be cut off, and the bad coordinates make it nearly impossible to cut off the theory without spoiling the symmetry.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This makes it difficult to extract the physical predictions, which require a careful limiting procedure.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The problem of lost symmetry also appears in classical mechanics, where the Hamiltonian formulation also superficially singles out time.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The Lagrangian formulation makes the relativistic invariance apparent.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] In the same way, the path integral is manifestly relativistic.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] It reproduces the Schrödinger equation, the Heisenberg equations of motion, and the canonical commutation relations and shows that they are compatible with relativity.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] It extends the Heisenberg-type operator algebra to operator product rules, which are new relations difficult to see in the old formalism.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Further, different choices of canonical variables lead to very different-seeming formulations of the same theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The transformations between the variables can be very complicated, but the path integral makes them into reasonably straightforward changes of integration variables.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] For these reasons, the Feynman path integral has made earlier formalisms largely obsolete.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The price of a path integral representation is that the unitarity of a theory is no longer self-evident, but it can be proven by changing variables to some canonical representation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The path integral itself also deals with larger mathematical spaces than is usual, which requires more careful mathematics, not all of which has been fully worked out.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The path integral historically was not immediately accepted, partly because it took many years to incorporate fermions properly.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This required physicists to invent an entirely new mathematical object – the Grassmann variable – which also allowed changes of variables to be done naturally, as well as allowing constrained quantization.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The integration variables in the path integral are subtly non-commuting.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The value of the product of two field operators at what looks like the same point depends on how the two points are ordered in space and time.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] In relativistic theories, there is both a particle and field representation for every theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The field representation is a sum over all field configurations, and the particle representation is a sum over different particle paths.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The nonrelativistic formulation is traditionally given in terms of particle paths, not fields.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] and in p-space the proportionality factor here is constant in time, as will be verified in a moment.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] which is the reciprocal of the operator that annihilates the wavefunction in the Schrödinger equation, which wouldn't have come out right if the proportionality factor weren't constant in the p-space representation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The infinitesimal term in the denominator is a small positive number, which guarantees that the inverse Fourier transform in E will be nonzero only for future times.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] For past times, the inverse Fourier transform contour closes toward values of E where there is no singularity.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This guarantees that K propagates the particle into the future and is the reason for the subscript "F" on G.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The infinitesimal term can be interpreted as an infinitesimal rotation toward imaginary time.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] It is also possible to reexpress the nonrelativistic time evolution in terms of propagators going toward the past, since the Schrödinger equation is time-reversible.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The past propagator is the same as the future propagator except for the obvious difference that it vanishes in the future, and in the Gaussian t is replaced by −*t*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Given the nearly identical only change is the sign of E and ε, the parameter E in Green's function can either be the energy if the paths are going toward the future, or the negative of the energy if the paths are going toward the past.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] For a nonrelativistic theory, the time as measured along the path of a moving particle and the time as measured by an outside observer are the same.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The integral above is not trivial to interpret because of the square root.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Fortunately, there is a heuristic trick.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The sum is over the relativistic arc length of the path of an oscillating quantity, and like the nonrelativistic path integral should be interpreted as slightly rotated into imaginary time.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This describes a sum over all paths of length Τ of the exponential of minus the length.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This can be given a probability interpretation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The sum over all paths is a probability average over a path constructed step by step.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The total number of steps is proportional to Τ, and each step is less likely the longer it is.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] where *W*(Τ) is a weight factor, the relative importance of paths of different proper time.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Taking a Fourier transform over the variable (*x* − *y*) can be done for each value of Τ separately, and because each separate Τ contribution is a Gaussian, gives whose Fourier transform is another Gaussian with reciprocal width.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] which is the Euclidean propagator for a scalar particle.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] For states where one nonrelativistic particle is present, the initial wavefunction has a frequency distribution concentrated near *p*0 = *m*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] When convolving with the propagator, which in p space just means multiplying by the propagator, the second term is suppressed and the first term is enhanced.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This is the expression for the nonrelativistic Green's function of a free Schrödinger particle.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The second term has a nonrelativistic limit also, but this limit is concentrated on frequencies that are negative.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The second pole is dominated by contributions from paths where the proper time and the coordinate time are ticking in an opposite sense, which means that the second term is to be interpreted as the antiparticle.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The nonrelativistic analysis shows that with this form the antiparticle still has positive energy.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The proper way to express this mathematically is that, adding a small suppression factor in proper time, the limit where *t* → −∞ of the first term must vanish, while the *t* → +∞ limit of the second term must vanish.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Without these terms, the pole contribution could not be unambiguously evaluated when taking the inverse Fourier transform of *p*0.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] which when factored, produces opposite-sign infinitesimal terms in each factor.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This is the mathematically precise form of the relativistic particle propagator, free of any ambiguities.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The ε term introduces a small imaginary part to the *α* = *m*2, which in the Minkowski version is a small exponential suppression of long paths.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] So in the relativistic case, the Feynman path-integral representation of the propagator includes paths going backwards in time, which describe antiparticles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Unlike the nonrelativistic case, it is impossible to produce a relativistic theory of local particle propagation without including antiparticles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] All local differential operators have inverses that are nonzero outside the light cone, meaning that it is impossible to keep a particle from travelling faster than light.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Such a particle cannot have a Green's function that is only nonzero in the future in a relativistically invariant theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] However, the path integral formulation is also extremely important in *direct* application to quantum field theory, in which the "paths" or histories being considered are not the motions of a single particle, but the possible time evolutions of a field over all space.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The action is referred to technically as a functional of the field: *S*[*ϕ*], where the field *ϕ*(*xμ*) is itself a function of space and time, and the square brackets are a reminder that the action depends on all the field's values everywhere, not just some particular value.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] *One* such given function *ϕ*(*xμ*) of spacetime is called a *field configuration*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] In principle, one integrates Feynman's amplitude over the class of all possible field configurations.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Much of the formal study of QFT is devoted to the properties of the resulting functional integral, and much effort (not yet entirely successful) has been made toward making these functional integrals mathematically precise.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Such a functional integral is extremely similar to the partition function in statistical mechanics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Indeed, it is sometimes *called* a partition function, and the two are essentially mathematically identical except for the factor of i in the exponent in Feynman's postulate 3.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Analytically continuing the integral to an imaginary time variable (called a Wick rotation) makes the functional integral even more like a statistical partition function and also tames some of the mathematical difficulties of working with these integrals.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The symbol ∫D*ϕ* here is a concise way to represent the infinite-dimensional integral over all possible field configurations on all of space-time.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] As stated above, the unadorned path integral in the denominator ensures proper normalization.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Strictly speaking, the only question that can be asked in physics is: *What fraction of states satisfying condition A also satisfy condition B?* The answer to this is a number between 0 and 1, which can be interpreted as a conditional probability, written as P(*B*|*A*).
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] where the functional *O*in[*ϕ*] is the superposition of all incoming states that could lead to the states we are interested in.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] In particular, this could be a state corresponding to the state of the Universe just after the Big Bang, although for actual calculation this can be simplified using heuristic methods.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Since this expression is a quotient of path integrals, it is naturally normalised.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Since this formulation of quantum mechanics is analogous to classical action principle, one might expect that identities concerning the action in classical mechanics would have quantum counterparts derivable from a functional integral.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] (the left-hand side is a functional derivative; the equation means that the action is stationary under small changes in the field configuration).
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The quantum analogues of these equations are called the Schwinger–Dyson equations.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] for any polynomially-bounded functional F.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] These equations are the analog of the on-shell EL equations.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The time ordering is taken before the time derivatives inside the S,*i*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Basically, if D*φ* *e**i*S[*φ*] is viewed as a functional distribution (this shouldn't be taken too literally as an interpretation of QFT, unlike its Wick-rotated statistical mechanics analogue, because we have time ordering complications here!), then ⟨*φ*(*x*1) ...
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] *φ*(*xn*)⟩ are its moments, and Z is its Fourier transform.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] If F is a functional of φ, then for an operator K, *F*[*K*] is defined to be the operator that substitutes K for φ.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] If the functional measure is not translationally invariant, it might be possible to express it as the product *M*[*φ*] D*φ*, where M is a functional and D*φ* is a translationally invariant measure.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This is true, for example, for nonlinear sigma models where the target space is diffeomorphic to **R***n*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] However, if the target manifold is some topologically nontrivial space, the concept of a translation does not even make any sense.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] If we expand this equation as a Taylor series about *J* = 0, we get the entire set of Schwinger–Dyson equations.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The path integrals are usually thought of as being the sum of all paths through an infinite space–time.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] However, in local quantum field theory we would restrict everything to lie within a finite *causally complete* region, for example inside a double light-cone.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This gives a more mathematically precise and physically rigorous definition of quantum field theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Now how about the on shell Noether's theorem for the classical case?
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The functional measure would have to be invariant under the one parameter group of symmetry transformation as well.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] for some function f where f only depends locally on φ (and possibly the spacetime position).
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] If we don't assume any special boundary conditions, this would not be a "true" symmetry in the true sense of the term in general unless *f* = 0 or something.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Here, Q is a derivation that generates the one parameter group in question.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] We could have antiderivations as well, such as BRST and supersymmetry.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This property is called the invariance of the measure, and this does not hold in general.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] where the integral is over the boundary.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This is the quantum analog of Noether's theorem.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] (this is assuming the Lagrangian only depends on φ and its first partial derivatives!
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] More general Lagrangians would require a modification to this definition!).
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] We're not insisting that *q*(*x*) is the generator of a symmetry (i.e. we are *not* insisting upon the gauge principle), but just that Q is.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The above two equations are the Ward–Takahashi identities.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Now for the case where *f* = 0, we can forget about all the boundary conditions and locality assumptions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Path integrals as they are defined here require the introduction of regulators.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Changing the scale of the regulator leads to the renormalization group.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] In fact, renormalization is the major obstruction to making path integrals well-defined.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] In one interpretation of quantum mechanics, the "sum over histories" interpretation, the path integral is taken to be fundamental, and reality is viewed as a single indistinguishable "class" of paths that all share the same events.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] For this interpretation, it is crucial to understand what exactly an event is.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] The sum-over-histories method gives identical results to canonical quantum mechanics, and Sinha and Sorkin claim the interpretation explains the Einstein–Podolsky–Rosen paradox without resorting to nonlocality.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Some advocates of interpretations of quantum mechanics emphasizing decoherence have attempted to make more rigorous the notion of extracting a classical-like "coarse-grained" history from the space of all possible histories.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Whereas in quantum mechanics the path integral formulation is fully equivalent to other formulations, it may be that it can be extended to quantum gravity, which would make it different from the Hilbert space model.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Feynman had some success in this direction, and his work has been extended by Hawking and others.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Approaches that use this method include causal dynamical triangulations and spinfoam models.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Quantum tunnelling can be modeled by using the path integral formation to determine the action of the trajectory through a potential barrier.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] with the effective action *S*eff and pre-exponential factor *A*o.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] This form is specifically useful in a dissipative system, in which the systems and surroundings must be modeled together.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] Using the Langevin equation to model Brownian motion, the path integral formation can be used to determine an effective action and pre-exponential model to see the effect of dissipation on tunnelling.
[src:quantum-field-theory/path-integral-formulation-p02] From this model, tunneling rates of macroscopic systems (at finite temperatures) can be predicted.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In theoretical physics, **quantum field theory** (**QFT**) is a theoretical framework that combines field theory, special relativity and quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] QFT is used in particle physics to construct physical models of subatomic particles and in condensed matter physics to construct models of quasiparticles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The current Standard Model of particle physics is based on QFT.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Despite its extraordinary predictive success, QFT faces ongoing challenges in fully incorporating gravity and in establishing a completely rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Quantum field theory emerged from the work of generations of theoretical physicists spanning much of the 20th century.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Its development began in the 1920s with the description of interactions between light and electrons, culminating in the first quantum field theory—quantum electrodynamics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] A major theoretical obstacle soon followed with the appearance and persistence of various infinities in perturbative calculations, a problem only resolved in the 1950s with the invention of the renormalization procedure.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] A second major barrier came with QFT's apparent inability to describe the weak and strong interactions, to the point where some theorists called for the abandonment of the field theoretic approach.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The development of gauge theory and the completion of the Standard Model in the 1970s led to a renaissance of quantum field theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Quantum field theory is the result of the combination of classical field theory, quantum mechanics, and special relativity.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] A brief overview of these theoretical precursors follows.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The earliest successful classical field theory is one that emerged from Newton's law of universal gravitation, despite the complete absence of the concept of fields from his 1687 treatise *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The force of gravity as described by Isaac Newton is an "action at a distance"—its effects on faraway objects are instantaneous, no matter the distance.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In an exchange of letters with Richard Bentley, however, Newton stated that "it is inconceivable that inanimate brute matter should, without the mediation of something else which is not material, operate upon and affect other matter without mutual contact".
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] It was not until the 18th century that mathematical physicists discovered a convenient description of gravity based on fields—a numerical quantity (a vector in the case of gravitational field) assigned to every point in space indicating the action of gravity on any particle at that point.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] However, this was considered merely a mathematical trick.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Fields began to take on an existence of their own with the development of electromagnetism in the 19th century.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Michael Faraday coined the English term "field" in 1845.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] He introduced fields as properties of space (even when it is devoid of matter) having physical effects.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] He argued against "action at a distance", and proposed that interactions between objects occur via space-filling "lines of force".
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] This description of fields remains to this day.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The theory of classical electromagnetism was completed in 1864 with Maxwell's equations, which described the relationship between the electric field, the magnetic field, electric current, and electric charge.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Maxwell's equations implied the existence of electromagnetic waves, a phenomenon whereby electric and magnetic fields propagate from one spatial point to another at a finite speed, which turns out to be the speed of light.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Action-at-a-distance was thus conclusively refuted.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Despite the enormous success of classical electromagnetism, it was unable to account for the discrete lines in atomic spectra, nor for the distribution of blackbody radiation in different wavelengths.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Max Planck's study of blackbody radiation marked the beginning of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] He treated atoms, which absorb and emit electromagnetic radiation, as tiny oscillators with the crucial property that their energies can only take on a series of discrete, rather than continuous, values.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] These are known as quantum harmonic oscillators.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] This process of restricting energies to discrete values is called quantization.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Building on this idea, Albert Einstein proposed in 1905 an explanation for the photoelectric effect, that light is composed of individual packets of energy called photons (the quanta of light).
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] This implied that the electromagnetic radiation, while being waves in the classical electromagnetic field, also exists in the form of particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In 1913, Niels Bohr introduced the Bohr model of atomic structure, wherein electrons within atoms can only take on a series of discrete, rather than continuous, energies.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] This is another example of quantization.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The Bohr model successfully explained the discrete nature of atomic spectral lines.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In 1924, Louis de Broglie proposed the hypothesis of wave–particle duality, that microscopic particles exhibit both wave-like and particle-like properties under different circumstances.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Uniting these scattered ideas, a coherent discipline, quantum mechanics, was formulated between 1925 and 1926, with important contributions from Max Planck, Louis de Broglie, Werner Heisenberg, Max Born, Erwin Schrödinger, Paul Dirac, and Wolfgang Pauli.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In the same year as his paper on the photoelectric effect, Einstein published his theory of special relativity, built on Maxwell's electromagnetism.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] New rules, called Lorentz transformations, were given for the way time and space coordinates of an event change under changes in the observer's velocity, and the distinction between time and space was blurred.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] It was proposed that all physical laws must be the same for observers at different velocities, i.e. that physical laws be invariant under Lorentz transformations.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Theoretically, the Schrödinger equation could not describe photons and was inconsistent with the principles of special relativity—it treats time as an ordinary number while promoting spatial coordinates to linear operators.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Quantum field theory naturally began with the study of electromagnetic interactions, as the electromagnetic field was the only known classical field as of the 1920s.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Through the works of Born, Heisenberg, and Pascual Jordan in 1925–1926, a quantum theory of the free electromagnetic field (one with no interactions with matter) was developed via canonical quantization by treating the electromagnetic field as a set of quantum harmonic oscillators.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] With the exclusion of interactions, however, such a theory was yet incapable of making quantitative predictions about the real world.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Using first-order perturbation theory, he successfully explained the phenomenon of spontaneous emission.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] According to the uncertainty principle in quantum mechanics, quantum harmonic oscillators cannot remain stationary, but they have a non-zero minimum energy and must always be oscillating, even in the lowest energy state (the ground state).
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Therefore, even in a perfect vacuum, there remains an oscillating electromagnetic field having zero-point energy.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] It is this quantum fluctuation of electromagnetic fields in the vacuum that "stimulates" the spontaneous emission of radiation by electrons in atoms.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Dirac's theory was hugely successful in explaining both the emission and absorption of radiation by atoms; by applying second-order perturbation theory, it was able to account for the scattering of photons, resonance fluorescence and non-relativistic Compton scattering.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Nonetheless, the application of higher-order perturbation theory was plagued with problematic infinities in calculations.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In 1928, Dirac wrote down a wave equation that described relativistic electrons: the Dirac equation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] It had the following important consequences: the spin of an electron is 1/2; the electron *g*-factor is 2; it led to the correct Sommerfeld formula for the fine structure of the hydrogen atom; and it could be used to derive the Klein–Nishina formula for relativistic Compton scattering.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Although the results were fruitful, the theory also apparently implied the existence of negative energy states, which would cause atoms to be unstable, since they could always decay to lower energy states by the emission of radiation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The prevailing view at the time was that the world was composed of two very different ingredients: material particles (such as electrons) and quantum fields (such as photons).
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Material particles were considered to be eternal, with their physical state described by the probabilities of finding each particle in any given region of space or range of velocities.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] On the other hand, photons were considered merely the excited states of the underlying quantized electromagnetic field, and could be freely created or destroyed.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] It was between 1928 and 1930 that Jordan, Eugene Wigner, Heisenberg, Pauli, and Enrico Fermi discovered that material particles could also be seen as excited states of quantum fields.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Just as photons are excited states of the quantized electromagnetic field, so each type of particle had its corresponding quantum field: an electron field, a proton field, etc.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Given enough energy, it would now be possible to create material particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Building on this idea, Fermi proposed in 1932 an explanation for beta decay known as Fermi's interaction.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Atomic nuclei do not contain electrons *per se*, but in the process of decay, an electron is created out of the surrounding electron field, analogous to the photon created from the surrounding electromagnetic field in the radiative decay of an excited atom.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] It was realized in 1929 by Dirac and others that negative energy states implied by the Dirac equation could be removed by assuming the existence of particles with the same mass as electrons but opposite electric charge.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] This not only ensured the stability of atoms, but it was also the first proposal of the existence of antimatter.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Indeed, the evidence for positrons was discovered in 1932 by Carl David Anderson in cosmic rays.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] With enough energy, such as by absorbing a photon, an electron-positron pair could be created, a process called pair production; the reverse process, annihilation, could also occur with the emission of a photon.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] This showed that particle numbers need not be fixed during an interaction.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Historically, however, positrons were at first thought of as "holes" in an infinite electron sea, rather than a new kind of particle, and this theory was referred to as the Dirac hole theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] QFT naturally incorporated antiparticles in its formalism.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] It was not until 20 years later that a systematic approach to remove such infinities was developed.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] A series of papers was published between 1934 and 1938 by Ernst Stueckelberg that established a relativistically invariant formulation of QFT.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In 1947, Stueckelberg also independently developed a complete renormalization procedure.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Such achievements were not understood and recognized by the theoretical community.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Faced with these infinities, John Archibald Wheeler and Heisenberg proposed, in 1937 and 1943 respectively, to supplant the problematic QFT with the so-called S-matrix theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In 1945, Richard Feynman and Wheeler daringly suggested abandoning QFT altogether and proposed action-at-a-distance as the mechanism of particle interactions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In 1947, Willis Lamb and Robert Retherford measured the minute difference in the 2*S*1/2 and 2*P*1/2 energy levels of the hydrogen atom, also called the Lamb shift.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] By ignoring the contribution of photons whose energy exceeds the electron mass, Hans Bethe successfully estimated the numerical value of the Lamb shift.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Subsequently, Norman Myles Kroll, Lamb, James Bruce French, and Victor Weisskopf again confirmed this value using an approach in which infinities cancelled other infinities to result in finite quantities.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] However, this method was clumsy and unreliable and could not be generalized to other calculations.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The breakthrough eventually came around 1950 when a more robust method for eliminating infinities was developed by Julian Schwinger, Richard Feynman, Freeman Dyson, and Shinichiro Tomonaga.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The main idea is to replace the calculated values of mass and charge, infinite though they may be, by their finite measured values.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] This systematic computational procedure is known as renormalization and can be applied to arbitrary order in perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] By applying the renormalization procedure, calculations were finally made to explain the electron's anomalous magnetic moment (the deviation of the electron *g*-factor from 2) and vacuum polarization.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] These results agreed with experimental measurements to a remarkable degree, thus marking the end of a "war against infinities".
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] At the same time, Feynman introduced the path integral formulation of quantum mechanics and Feynman diagrams.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The latter can be used to visually and intuitively organize and to help compute terms in the perturbative expansion.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Each diagram can be interpreted as paths of particles in an interaction, with each vertex and line having a corresponding mathematical expression, and the product of these expressions gives the scattering amplitude of the interaction represented by the diagram.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] It was with the invention of the renormalization procedure and Feynman diagrams that QFT finally arose as a complete theoretical framework.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Given the tremendous success of QED, many theorists believed, in the few years after 1949, that QFT could soon provide an understanding of all microscopic phenomena, not only the interactions between photons, electrons, and positrons.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Contrary to this optimism, QFT entered yet another period of depression that lasted for almost two decades.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The first obstacle was the limited applicability of the renormalization procedure.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In perturbative calculations in QED, all infinite quantities could be eliminated by redefining a small (finite) number of physical quantities (namely the mass and charge of the electron).
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Dyson proved in 1949 that this is only possible for a small class of theories called "renormalizable theories", of which QED is an example.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] However, most theories, including the Fermi theory of the weak interaction, are "non-renormalizable".
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Any perturbative calculation in these theories beyond the first order would result in infinities that could not be removed by redefining a finite number of physical quantities.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The second major problem stemmed from the limited validity of the Feynman diagram method, which is based on a series expansion in perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In order for the series to converge and low-order calculations to be a good approximation, the coupling constant, in which the series is expanded, must be a sufficiently small number.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The coupling constant in QED is the fine-structure constant *α* ≈ 1/137, which is small enough that only the simplest, lowest order, Feynman diagrams need to be considered in realistic calculations.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In contrast, the coupling constant in the strong interaction is roughly of the order of one, making complicated, higher order, Feynman diagrams just as important as simple ones.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] There was thus no way of deriving reliable quantitative predictions for the strong interaction using perturbative QFT methods.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] With these difficulties looming, many theorists began to turn away from QFT.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Some focused on symmetry principles and conservation laws, while others picked up the old S-matrix theory of Wheeler and Heisenberg.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] QFT was used heuristically as guiding principles, but not as a basis for quantitative calculations.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Schwinger, however, took a different route.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] For more than a decade he and his students had been nearly the only exponents of field theory, but in 1951 he found a way around the problem of the infinities with a new method using *external sources* as currents coupled to gauge fields.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Motivated by the former findings, Schwinger kept pursuing this approach in order to "quantumly" generalize the classical process of coupling external forces to the configuration space parameters known as Lagrange multipliers.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In source theory there are no divergences, and no renormalization.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] It may be regarded as the calculational tool of field theory, but it is more general.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Using source theory, Schwinger was able to calculate the anomalous magnetic moment of the electron, which he had done in 1947, but this time with no 'distracting remarks' about infinite quantities.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Schwinger also applied source theory to his QFT theory of gravity, and was able to reproduce all four of Einstein's classic results: gravitational red shift, deflection and slowing of light by gravity, and the perihelion precession of Mercury.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In 1954, Yang Chen-Ning and Robert Mills generalized the local symmetry of QED, leading to non-Abelian gauge theories (also known as Yang–Mills theories), which are based on more complicated local symmetry groups.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In QED, (electrically) charged particles interact via the exchange of photons, while in non-Abelian gauge theory, particles carrying a new type of "charge" interact via the exchange of massless gauge bosons.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Unlike photons, these gauge bosons themselves carry charge.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Sheldon Glashow developed a non-Abelian gauge theory that unified the electromagnetic and weak interactions in 1960.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In 1964, Abdus Salam and John Clive Ward arrived at the same theory through a different path.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] This theory, nevertheless, was non-renormalizable.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] By combining the earlier theory of Glashow, Salam, and Ward with the idea of spontaneous symmetry breaking, Steven Weinberg wrote down in 1967 a theory describing electroweak interactions between all leptons and the effects of the Higgs boson.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] His theory was at first mostly ignored, until it was brought back to light in 1971 by Gerard 't Hooft's proof that non-Abelian gauge theories are renormalizable.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The electroweak theory of Weinberg and Salam was extended from leptons to quarks in 1970 by Glashow, John Iliopoulos, and Luciano Maiani, marking its completion.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Harald Fritzsch, Murray Gell-Mann, and Heinrich Leutwyler discovered in 1971 that certain phenomena involving the strong interaction could also be explained by non-Abelian gauge theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] In 1973, David Gross, Frank Wilczek, and Hugh David Politzer showed that non-Abelian gauge theories are "asymptotically free", meaning that under renormalization, the coupling constant of the strong interaction decreases as the interaction energy increases.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] These theoretical breakthroughs brought about a renaissance in QFT.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The full theory, which includes the electroweak theory and chromodynamics, is referred to today as the Standard Model of elementary particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The Standard Model successfully describes all fundamental interactions except gravity, and its many predictions have been met with remarkable experimental confirmation in subsequent decades.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The Higgs boson, central to the mechanism of spontaneous symmetry breaking, was finally detected in 2012 at CERN, marking the complete verification of the existence of all constituents of the Standard Model.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The 1970s saw the development of non-perturbative methods in non-Abelian gauge theories.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The 't Hooft–Polyakov monopole was discovered theoretically by 't Hooft and Alexander Polyakov, flux tubes by Holger Bech Nielsen and Poul Olesen, and instantons by Polyakov and coauthors.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] These objects are inaccessible through perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Supersymmetry also appeared in the same period.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The first supersymmetric QFT in four dimensions was built by Yuri Golfand and Evgeny Likhtman in 1970, but their result failed to garner widespread interest due to the Iron Curtain.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Supersymmetry theories only took off in the theoretical community after the work of Julius Wess and Bruno Zumino in 1973, but to date have not been widely accepted as part of the Standard Model due to lack of experimental evidence.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Among the four fundamental interactions, gravity remains the only one that lacks a consistent QFT description.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Various attempts at a theory of quantum gravity led to the development of string theory, itself a type of two-dimensional QFT with conformal symmetry.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Joël Scherk and John Schwarz first proposed in 1974 that string theory could be *the* quantum theory of gravity.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Although quantum field theory arose from the study of interactions between elementary particles, it has been successfully applied to other physical systems, particularly to many-body systems in condensed matter physics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Historically, the Higgs mechanism of spontaneous symmetry breaking was a result of Yoichiro Nambu's application of superconductor theory to elementary particles, while the concept of renormalization came out of the study of second-order phase transitions in matter.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Soon after the introduction of photons, Einstein performed the quantization procedure on vibrations in a crystal, leading to the first quasiparticle—phonons.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Lev Landau claimed that low-energy excitations in many condensed matter systems could be described in terms of interactions between a set of quasiparticles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] The Feynman diagram method of QFT was naturally well suited to the analysis of various phenomena in condensed matter systems.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p01] Gauge theory is used to describe the quantization of magnetic flux in superconductors, the resistivity in the quantum Hall effect, as well as the relation between frequency and voltage in the AC Josephson effect.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For simplicity, natural units are used in the following sections, in which the reduced Planck constant *ħ* and the speed of light *c* are both set to one.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] A classical field is a function of spatial and time coordinates.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Examples include the gravitational field **g**(**x**, *t*) in Newtonian gravity and the electric field **E**(**x**, *t*) and magnetic field **B**(**x**, *t*) in classical electromagnetism.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] A classical field can be thought of as a numerical quantity assigned to every point in space that changes in time.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Hence, it has infinitely many degrees of freedom.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Many phenomena exhibiting quantum mechanical properties cannot be explained by classical fields alone.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Phenomena such as the photoelectric effect are best explained by discrete particles (photons), rather than a spatially continuous field.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The goal of quantum field theory is to describe various quantum mechanical phenomena using a modified concept of fields.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Canonical quantization and path integrals are two common formulations of QFT.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] To motivate the fundamentals of QFT, an overview of classical field theory follows.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The simplest classical field is a real scalar field — a real number at every point in space that changes in time.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] It is denoted as *ϕ*(**x**, *t*), where **x** is the position vector, and *t* is the time.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The quantization procedure for the above classical field to a quantum operator field is analogous to the promotion of a classical harmonic oscillator to a quantum harmonic oscillator.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The displacement of a classical harmonic oscillator is described by $x(t)={\frac {1}{\sqrt {2\omega }}}ae^{-i\omega t}+{\frac {1}{\sqrt {2\omega }}}a^{*}e^{i\omega t},$ where *a* is a complex number (normalized by convention), and *ω* is the oscillator's frequency.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Note that *x* is the displacement of a particle in simple harmonic motion from the equilibrium position, not to be confused with the spatial label **x** of a quantum field.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For example, the state ${\hat {a}}^{\dagger }|0\rangle$ is an eigenstate of energy $3\hbar \omega /2$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] While the state space of a single quantum harmonic oscillator contains all the discrete energy states of one oscillating particle, the state space of a quantum field contains the discrete energy levels of an arbitrary number of particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The latter space is known as a Fock space, which can account for the fact that particle numbers are not fixed in relativistic quantum systems.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The process of quantizing an arbitrary number of particles instead of a single particle is often also called second quantization.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The foregoing procedure is a direct application of non-relativistic quantum mechanics and can be used to quantize (complex) scalar fields, Dirac fields, vector fields (*e.g.* the electromagnetic field), and even strings.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] However, creation and annihilation operators are only well defined in the simplest theories that contain no interactions (so-called free theory).
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In the case of the real scalar field, the existence of these operators was a consequence of the decomposition of solutions of the classical equations of motion into a sum of normal modes.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] To perform calculations on any realistic interacting theory, perturbation theory would be necessary.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The Lagrangian of any quantum field in nature would contain interaction terms in addition to the free theory terms.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The summation over the index *μ* has been omitted following the Einstein notation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] If the parameter *λ* is sufficiently small, then the interacting theory described by the above Lagrangian can be considered as a small perturbation from the free theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The path integral formulation of QFT is concerned with the direct computation of the scattering amplitude of a certain interaction process, rather than the establishment of operators and state spaces.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] To calculate the probability amplitude for a system to evolve from some initial state $|\phi _{I}\rangle$ at time *t* = 0 to some final state $|\phi _{F}\rangle$ at *t* = *T*, the total time *T* is divided into *N* small intervals.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The overall amplitude is the product of the amplitude of evolution within each interval, integrated over all intermediate states.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In calculations, one often encounters expression like $\langle 0|T\{\phi (x)\phi (y)\}|0\rangle \quad {\text{or}}\quad \langle \Omega |T\{\phi (x)\phi (y)\}|\Omega \rangle$ in the free or interacting theory, respectively.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] This expression represents the probability amplitude for the field to propagate from *y* to *x*, and goes by multiple names, like the two-point propagator, two-point correlation function, two-point Green's function or two-point function for short.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] However, through both the canonical quantization formulation and the path integral formulation, it is possible to express it through an infinite perturbation series of the *free* two-point function.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Here, the exponential should be understood as its power series expansion.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] As in the previous paragraph, the exponential can be expanded as a series in *λ*, reducing the interacting two-point function to quantities in the free theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Wick's theorem further reduce any *n*-point correlation function in the free theory to a sum of products of two-point correlation functions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] This makes the Feynman propagator one of the most important quantities in quantum field theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Correlation functions in the interacting theory can be written as a perturbation series.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Each term in the series is a product of Feynman propagators in the free theory and can be represented visually by a Feynman diagram.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Every vertex corresponds to a single $\phi$ field factor at the corresponding point in spacetime, while the edges correspond to the propagators between the spacetime points.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For every edge that connects two vertices $z_{i}$ and $z_{j}$ , write down a factor $D_{F}(z_{i}-z_{j})$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Divide by the symmetry factor of the diagram.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] With the symmetry factor 2 , following these rules yields exactly the expression above.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] By Fourier transforming the propagator, the Feynman rules can be reformulated from position space into momentum space.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In order to compute the *n*-point correlation function to the *k*-th order, list all valid Feynman diagrams with *n* external points and *k* or fewer vertices, and then use Feynman rules to obtain the expression for each term.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] To be precise, $\langle \Omega |T\{\phi (x_{1})\cdots \phi (x_{n})\}|\Omega \rangle$ is equal to the sum of (expressions corresponding to) all connected diagrams with *n* external points.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] (Connected diagrams are those in which every vertex is connected to an external point through lines.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Components that are totally disconnected from external lines are sometimes called "vacuum bubbles".) In the *ϕ*4 interaction theory discussed above, every vertex must have four legs.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In realistic applications, the scattering amplitude of a certain interaction or the decay rate of a particle can be computed from the S-matrix, which itself can be found using the Feynman diagram method.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Feynman diagrams devoid of "loops" are called tree-level diagrams, which describe the lowest-order interaction processes; those containing *n* loops are referred to as *n*-loop diagrams, which describe higher-order contributions, or radiative corrections, to the interaction.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Lines whose end points are vertices can be thought of as the propagation of virtual particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Feynman rules can be used to directly evaluate tree-level diagrams.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] However, naïve computation of loop diagrams such as the one shown above will result in divergent momentum integrals, which seems to imply that almost all terms in the perturbative expansion are infinite.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The renormalisation procedure is a systematic process for removing such infinities.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Parameters appearing in the Lagrangian, such as the mass *m* and the coupling constant *λ*, have no physical meaning — *m*, *λ*, and the field strength *ϕ* are not experimentally measurable quantities and are referred to here as the bare mass, bare coupling constant, and bare field, respectively.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The physical mass and coupling constant are measured in some interaction process and are generally different from the bare quantities.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] While computing physical quantities from this interaction process, one may limit the domain of divergent momentum integrals to be below some momentum cut-off Λ, obtain expressions for the physical quantities, and then take the limit Λ → ∞.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] This is an example of regularization, a class of methods to treat divergences in QFT, with Λ being the regulator.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The approach illustrated above is called bare perturbation theory, as calculations involve only the bare quantities such as mass and coupling constant.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] A different approach, called renormalized perturbation theory, is to use physically meaningful quantities from the very beginning.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In the case of *ϕ*4 theory, the field strength is first redefined: $\phi =Z^{1/2}\phi _{r},$ where *ϕ* is the bare field, *ϕr* is the renormalized field, and *Z* is a constant to be determined.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The first three terms are the *ϕ*4 Lagrangian density written in terms of the renormalized quantities, while the latter three terms are referred to as "counterterms".
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] As the Lagrangian now contains more terms, so the Feynman diagrams should include additional elements, each with their own Feynman rules.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] First select a regularization scheme (such as the cut-off regularization introduced above or dimensional regularization); call the regulator Λ.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Compute Feynman diagrams, in which divergent terms will depend on Λ.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Then, define *δZ*, *δm*, and *δλ* such that Feynman diagrams for the counterterms will exactly cancel the divergent terms in the normal Feynman diagrams when the limit Λ → ∞ is taken.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In this way, meaningful finite quantities are obtained.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] It is only possible to eliminate all infinities to obtain a finite result in renormalizable theories, whereas in non-renormalizable theories infinities cannot be removed by the redefinition of a small number of parameters.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The Standard Model of elementary particles is a renormalizable QFT, while quantum gravity is non-renormalizable.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The renormalization group, developed by Kenneth Wilson, is a mathematical apparatus used to study the changes in physical parameters (coefficients in the Lagrangian) as the system is viewed at different scales.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The way in which each parameter changes with scale is described by its *β* function.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Correlation functions, which underlie quantitative physical predictions, change with scale according to the Callan–Symanzik equation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] This differential equation implies that the observed elementary charge increases as the scale increases.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The renormalized coupling constant, which changes with the energy scale, is also called the running coupling constant.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In the case where *Nf* ≤ 16 (the Standard Model has *Nf* = 6), the coupling constant *g* decreases as the energy scale increases.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Hence, while the strong interaction is strong at low energies, it becomes very weak in high-energy interactions, a phenomenon known as asymptotic freedom.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Conformal field theories (CFTs) are special QFTs that admit conformal symmetry.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] They are insensitive to changes in the scale, as all their coupling constants have vanishing *β* function.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] (The converse is not true, however — the vanishing of all *β* functions does not imply conformal symmetry of the theory.) Examples include string theory and *N* = 4 supersymmetric Yang–Mills theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] According to Wilson's picture, every QFT is fundamentally accompanied by its energy cut-off Λ, *i.e.* that the theory is no longer valid at energies higher than Λ, and all degrees of freedom above the scale Λ are to be omitted.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For example, the cut-off could be the inverse of the atomic spacing in a condensed matter system, and in elementary particle physics it could be associated with the fundamental "graininess" of spacetime caused by quantum fluctuations in gravity.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The cut-off scale of theories of particle interactions lies far beyond current experiments.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Even if the theory were very complicated at that scale, as long as its couplings are sufficiently weak, it must be described at low energies by a renormalizable effective field theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The difference between renormalizable and non-renormalizable theories is that the former are insensitive to details at high energies, whereas the latter do depend on them.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] According to this view, non-renormalizable theories are to be seen as low-energy effective theories of a more fundamental theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The failure to remove the cut-off Λ from calculations in such a theory merely indicates that new physical phenomena appear at scales above Λ, where a new theory is necessary.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The quantization and renormalization procedures outlined in the preceding sections are performed for the free theory and *ϕ*4 theory of the real scalar field.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] A similar process can be done for other types of fields, including the complex scalar field, the vector field, and the Dirac field, as well as other types of interaction terms, including the electromagnetic interaction and the Yukawa interaction.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] As an example, quantum electrodynamics contains a Dirac field *ψ* representing the electron field and a vector field *Aμ* representing the electromagnetic field (photon field).
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The parameters in this theory are the (bare) electron mass *m* and the (bare) elementary charge *e*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The first and second terms in the Lagrangian density correspond to the free Dirac field and free vector fields, respectively.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The last term describes the interaction between the electron and photon fields, which is treated as a perturbation from the free theories.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Shown above is an example of a tree-level Feynman diagram in QED.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] It describes an electron and a positron annihilating, creating an off-shell photon, and then decaying into a new pair of electron and positron.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Arrows pointing forward in time represent the propagation of electrons, while those pointing backward in time represent the propagation of positrons.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] A wavy line represents the propagation of a photon.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Each vertex in QED Feynman diagrams must have an incoming and an outgoing fermion (positron/electron) leg as well as a photon leg.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] If a theory's Lagrangian (or more precisely the action) is invariant under a certain local transformation, then the transformation is referred to as a gauge symmetry of the theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Gauge symmetries form a group at every spacetime point.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In the case of QED, the successive application of two different local symmetry transformations $e^{i\alpha (x)}$ and $e^{i\alpha '(x)}$ is yet another symmetry transformation $e^{i[\alpha (x)+\alpha '(x)]}$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For any *α*(*x*), $e^{i\alpha (x)}$ is an element of the U(1) group, thus QED is said to have U(1) gauge symmetry.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The photon field *Aμ* may be referred to as the U(1) gauge boson.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] U(1) is an Abelian group, meaning that the result is the same regardless of the order in which its elements are applied.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] QFTs can also be built on non-Abelian groups, giving rise to non-Abelian gauge theories (also known as Yang–Mills theories).
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Quantum chromodynamics, which describes the strong interaction, is a non-Abelian gauge theory with an SU(3) gauge symmetry.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] It contains three Dirac fields *ψi*, *i* = 1,2,3 representing quark fields as well as eight vector fields *Aa,μ*, *a* = 1,...,8 representing gluon fields, which are the SU(3) gauge bosons.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Repeated indices *i*,*j*,*a* are implicitly summed over following Einstein notation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The preceding discussion of symmetries is on the level of the Lagrangian.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In other words, these are "classical" symmetries.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] After quantization, some theories will no longer exhibit their classical symmetries, a phenomenon called anomaly.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For instance, in the path integral formulation, despite the invariance of the Lagrangian density ${\mathcal {L}}[\phi ,\partial _{\mu }\phi ]$ under a certain local transformation of the fields, the measure ${\textstyle \int {\mathcal {D}}\phi }$ of the path integral may change.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For a theory describing nature to be consistent, it must not contain any anomaly in its gauge symmetry.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The Standard Model of elementary particles is a gauge theory based on the group SU(3) × SU(2) × U(1), in which all anomalies exactly cancel.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The theoretical foundation of general relativity, the equivalence principle, can also be understood as a form of gauge symmetry, making general relativity a gauge theory based on the Lorentz group.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Noether's theorem states that every continuous symmetry, *i.e.* the parameter in the symmetry transformation being continuous rather than discrete, leads to a corresponding conservation law.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For example, the U(1) symmetry of QED implies charge conservation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Gauge-transformations do not relate distinct quantum states.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Rather, it relates two equivalent mathematical descriptions of the same quantum state.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] As an example, the photon field *Aμ*, being a four-vector, has four apparent degrees of freedom, but the actual state of a photon is described by its two degrees of freedom corresponding to the polarization.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The remaining two degrees of freedom are said to be "redundant" — apparently different ways of writing *Aμ* can be related to each other by a gauge transformation and in fact describe the same state of the photon field.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In this sense, gauge invariance is not a "real" symmetry, but a reflection of the "redundancy" of the chosen mathematical description.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] To account for the gauge redundancy in the path integral formulation, one must perform the so-called Faddeev–Popov gauge fixing procedure.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In non-Abelian gauge theories, such a procedure introduces new fields called "ghosts".
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Particles corresponding to the ghost fields are called ghost particles, which cannot be detected externally.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] A more rigorous generalization of the Faddeev–Popov procedure is given by BRST quantization.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Spontaneous symmetry breaking is a mechanism whereby the symmetry of the Lagrangian is violated by the system described by it.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The original O(*N*) global symmetry is no longer manifest, leaving only the subgroup O(*N* − 1).
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The larger symmetry before spontaneous symmetry breaking is said to be "hidden" or spontaneously broken.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Goldstone's theorem states that under spontaneous symmetry breaking, every broken continuous global symmetry leads to a massless field called the Goldstone boson.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In the above example, O(*N*) has *N*(*N* − 1)/2 continuous symmetries (the dimension of its Lie algebra), while O(*N* − 1) has (*N* − 1)(*N* − 2)/2.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The number of broken symmetries is their difference, *N* − 1, which corresponds to the *N* − 1 massless fields *πk*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] On the other hand, when a gauge (as opposed to global) symmetry is spontaneously broken, the resulting Goldstone boson is "eaten" by the corresponding gauge boson by becoming an additional degree of freedom for the gauge boson.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The Goldstone boson equivalence theorem states that at high energy, the amplitude for emission or absorption of a longitudinally polarized massive gauge boson becomes equal to the amplitude for emission or absorption of the Goldstone boson that was eaten by the gauge boson.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In the QFT of ferromagnetism, spontaneous symmetry breaking can explain the alignment of magnetic dipoles at low temperatures.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In the Standard Model of elementary particles, the W and Z bosons, which would otherwise be massless as a result of gauge symmetry, acquire mass through spontaneous symmetry breaking of the Higgs boson, a process called the Higgs mechanism.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] All experimentally known symmetries in nature relate bosons to bosons and fermions to fermions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Theorists have hypothesized the existence of a type of symmetry, called supersymmetry, that relates bosons and fermions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The Standard Model obeys Poincaré symmetry, whose generators are the spacetime translations *Pμ* and the Lorentz transformations *Jμν*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In addition to these generators, supersymmetry in (3+1)-dimensions includes additional generators *Qα*, called supercharges, which themselves transform as Weyl fermions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The symmetry group generated by all these generators is known as the super-Poincaré group.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In general there can be more than one set of supersymmetry generators, *QαI*, *I* = 1, ..., *N*, which generate the corresponding *N* = 1 supersymmetry, *N* = 2 supersymmetry, and so on.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Supersymmetry can also be constructed in other dimensions, most notably in (1+1) dimensions for its application in superstring theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The Lagrangian of a supersymmetric theory must be invariant under the action of the super-Poincaré group.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Examples of such theories include: Minimal Supersymmetric Standard Model (MSSM), *N* = 4 supersymmetric Yang–Mills theory, and superstring theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In a supersymmetric theory, every fermion has a bosonic superpartner and vice versa.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] If supersymmetry is promoted to a local symmetry, then the resultant gauge theory is an extension of general relativity called supergravity.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Supersymmetry is a potential solution to many current problems in physics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For example, the hierarchy problem of the Standard Model—why the mass of the Higgs boson is not radiatively corrected (under renormalization) to a very high scale such as the grand unified scale or the Planck scale—can be resolved by relating the Higgs field and its super-partner, the Higgsino.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Radiative corrections due to Higgs boson loops in Feynman diagrams are cancelled by corresponding Higgsino loops.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Supersymmetry also offers answers to the grand unification of all gauge coupling constants in the Standard Model as well as the nature of dark matter.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Nevertheless, experiments have yet to provide evidence for the existence of supersymmetric particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] If supersymmetry were a true symmetry of nature, then it must be a broken symmetry, and the energy of symmetry breaking must be higher than those achievable by present-day experiments.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The *ϕ*4 theory, QED, QCD, as well as the whole Standard Model all assume a (3+1)-dimensional Minkowski space (3 spatial and 1 time dimensions) as the background on which the quantum fields are defined.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] However, QFT *a priori* imposes no restriction on the number of dimensions nor the geometry of spacetime.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In condensed matter physics, QFT is used to describe (2+1)-dimensional electron gases.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In high-energy physics, string theory is a type of (1+1)-dimensional QFT, while Kaluza–Klein theory uses gravity in extra dimensions to produce gauge theories in lower dimensions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For a real scalar field, the Lagrangian density in a general spacetime background is ${\mathcal {L}}={\sqrt {|g|}}\left({\frac {1}{2}}g^{\mu \nu }\nabla _{\mu }\phi \nabla _{\nu }\phi -{\frac {1}{2}}m^{2}\phi ^{2}\right),$ where *g* = det(*gμν*), and ∇*μ* denotes the covariant derivative.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The Lagrangian of a QFT, hence its calculational results and physical predictions, depends on the geometry of the spacetime background.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The correlation functions and physical predictions of a QFT depend on the spacetime metric *gμν*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For a special class of QFTs called topological quantum field theories (TQFTs), all correlation functions are independent of continuous changes in the spacetime metric.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] QFTs in curved spacetime generally change according to the *geometry* (local structure) of the spacetime background, while TQFTs are invariant under spacetime diffeomorphisms but are sensitive to the *topology* (global structure) of spacetime.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] This means that all calculational results of TQFTs are topological invariants of the underlying spacetime.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Chern–Simons theory is an example of TQFT and has been used to construct models of quantum gravity.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Applications of TQFT include the fractional quantum Hall effect and topological quantum computers.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The world line trajectory of fractionalized particles (known as anyons) can form a link configuration in the spacetime, which relates the braiding statistics of anyons in physics to the link invariants in mathematics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Topological quantum field theories (TQFTs) applicable to the frontier research of topological quantum matters include Chern-Simons-Witten gauge theories in 2+1 spacetime dimensions, other new exotic TQFTs in 3+1 spacetime dimensions and beyond.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Using perturbation theory, the total effect of a small interaction term can be approximated order by order by a series expansion in the number of virtual particles participating in the interaction.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Every term in the expansion may be understood as one possible way for (physical) particles to interact with each other via virtual particles, expressed visually using a Feynman diagram.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The electromagnetic force between two electrons in QED is represented (to first order in perturbation theory) by the propagation of a virtual photon.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In a similar manner, the W and Z bosons carry the weak interaction, while gluons carry the strong interaction.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The interpretation of an interaction as a sum of intermediate states involving the exchange of various virtual particles only makes sense in the framework of perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In contrast, non-perturbative methods in QFT treat the interacting Lagrangian as a whole without any series expansion.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Instead of particles that carry interactions, these methods have spawned such concepts as 't Hooft–Polyakov monopole, domain wall, flux tube, and instanton.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Examples of QFTs that are completely solvable non-perturbatively include minimal models of conformal field theory and the Thirring model.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] In spite of its overwhelming success in particle physics and condensed matter physics, QFT itself lacks a formal mathematical foundation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] For example, according to Haag's theorem, there does not exist a well-defined interaction picture for QFT, which implies that perturbation theory of QFT, which underlies the entire Feynman diagram method, is fundamentally ill-defined.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] However, *perturbative* quantum field theory, which only requires that quantities be computable as a formal power series without any convergence requirements, can be given a rigorous mathematical treatment.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Furthermore, perturbative path-integral methods, typically understood as formal computational methods inspired from finite-dimensional integration theory, can be given a sound mathematical interpretation from their finite-dimensional analogues.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Since the 1950s, theoretical physicists and mathematicians have attempted to organize all QFTs into a set of axioms, in order to establish the existence of concrete models of relativistic QFT in a mathematically rigorous way and to study their properties.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Compared to ordinary QFT, topological quantum field theory and conformal field theory are better supported mathematically — both can be classified in the framework of representations of cobordisms.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Algebraic quantum field theory is another approach to the axiomatization of QFT, in which the fundamental objects are local operators and the algebraic relations between them.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Axiomatic systems following this approach include Wightman axioms and Haag–Kastler axioms.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] One way to construct theories satisfying Wightman axioms is to use Osterwalder–Schrader axioms, which give the necessary and sufficient conditions for a real time theory to be obtained from an imaginary time theory by analytic continuation (Wick rotation).
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] Yang–Mills existence and mass gap, one of the Millennium Prize Problems, concerns the well-defined existence of Yang–Mills theories as set out by the above axioms.
[src:quantum-field-theory/quantum-field-theory-p02] The full problem statement is as follows.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] For example, an electron theory may begin by postulating an electron with an initial mass and charge.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] In quantum field theory a cloud of virtual particles, such as photons, positrons, and others surrounds and interacts with the initial electron.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Accounting for the interactions of the surrounding particles (e.g. collisions at different energies) shows that the electron-system behaves as if it had a different mass and charge than initially postulated.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Renormalization, in this example, mathematically replaces the initially postulated mass and charge of an electron (the bare particle) with the experimentally observed mass and charge (the dressed particle).
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Mathematics and experiments prove that positrons and more massive particles such as protons exhibit precisely the same observed charge as the electron – even in the presence of much stronger interactions and more intense clouds of virtual particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Renormalization procedures are based on the requirement that certain physical quantities (such as the mass and charge of an electron) equal observed (experimental) values.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Renormalization specifies relationships between parameters in the theory when parameters describing large distance scales differ from parameters describing small distance scales.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Physically, the pileup of contributions from an infinite number of scales involved in a problem may then result in further infinite quantities.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] When describing spacetime as a continuum, certain statistical and quantum mechanical constructions are not well-defined.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] To define them unambiguously, a continuum limit must carefully remove "construction scaffolding" of lattices at various scales.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Renormalization was first developed in quantum electrodynamics (QED) to make sense of infinite integrals in perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Initially viewed as a suspect provisional procedure even by some of its originators, renormalization eventually was embraced as an important and self-consistent actual mechanism of scale physics in several fields of physics and mathematics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Despite his later skepticism, it was Paul Dirac who pioneered renormalization.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Today, on the basis of the breakthrough renormalization group insights of Nikolay Bogolyubov and Kenneth Wilson, the focus of studies of renormalization is on variation of physical quantities across contiguous scales; distant scales are instead related to each other through "effective" descriptions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] All scales are linked in a broadly systematic way, and the actual physics pertinent to each is extracted with suitable computational techniques appropriate for each.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Wilson clarified which variables of a system are crucial and which are redundant.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Renormalization is performed by setting a "renormalization scheme", equations which determine how the physical parameters are rescaled within the theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Different approaches such as on-shell or minimal subtraction are required depending on the type of interaction being considered.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Renormalization is distinct from regularization, another technique to control infinities by assuming the existence of new unknown physics at new scales, though the two can be used in tandem.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The problem of infinities first arose in the classical electrodynamics of point particles in the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The mass of a charged particle should include the mass–energy in its electrostatic field (electromagnetic mass).
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Assume that the particle is a charged spherical shell of radius *r*e.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This implies that the point particle would have infinite inertia and thus cannot be accelerated.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The total effective mass of a spherical charged particle includes the actual bare mass of the spherical shell (in addition to the mass mentioned above associated with its electric field).
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] If the shell's bare mass is allowed to be negative, it might be possible to take a consistent point limit.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This was called renormalization, and Lorentz and Abraham attempted to develop a classical theory of the electron this way.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This early work was the inspiration for later attempts at regularization and renormalization in quantum field theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] When calculating the electromagnetic interactions of charged particles, the back-reaction of a particle's own field on itself (analogous to the back-EMF of circuit analysis.) is necessary to explain the friction on charged particles when they emit radiation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] If the electron is assumed to be a point, the value of the back-reaction diverges, for the same reason that the mass diverges, because the field is inverse-square.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The Abraham–Lorentz theory includes a retrocausal "pre-acceleration", allowing solution where an electron would start moving *before* the force is applied.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] These problems remain in the relativistic version of the Abraham-Lorentz equation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This is a sign that the point limit is inconsistent, and/or that a quantum mechanical treatment is required.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] In quantum electrodynamics at small coupling, the electromagnetic mass only diverges as the logarithm of the radius of the particle.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] One way of describing the perturbation theory corrections' divergences was discovered in 1947–49 by Hans Kramers, Hans Bethe, Julian Schwinger, Richard Feynman, and Shin'ichiro Tomonaga, and systematized by Freeman Dyson in 1949.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The divergences appear in radiative corrections involving Feynman diagrams with closed loops of virtual particles in them.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] While virtual particles obey conservation of energy and momentum, they can have any energy and momentum, even off-shell ones that are not allowed by the relativistic energy–momentum relation for the observed mass of that particle.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] When there is a loop, the momentum of the particles involved in the loop is not uniquely determined by the energies and momenta of incoming and outgoing particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] A variation in the energy of one particle in the loop can be balanced by an equal and opposite change in the energy of another particle in the loop, without affecting the incoming and outgoing particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Finding the amplitude for the loop process requires integration over all possible combinations of energy and momentum that could travel around the loop.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] An electron quickly emits and reabsorbs a virtual photon, called a self-energy.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This diagram adjusts the mass of the electron.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] An electron emits a photon, emits a second photon, and reabsorbs the first.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This process is shown in the section below in figure 2 as a "penguin diagram", and it is called a *vertex renormalization*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This provides corrections to the electron charge.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The second class of divergence called an infrared divergence.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Every process involving charged particles emits infinitely many coherent photons of infinite wavelength, and the amplitude for emitting any finite number of photons is zero.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] For example, at the one-loop order, the vertex function has both ultraviolet and infrared divergences.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] In contrast to the ultraviolet divergence, the infrared divergence does not require the renormalization of a parameter in the theory involved.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This additional diagram must be included because there is no physical way to distinguish a zero-energy photon flowing through a loop as in the vertex diagram and zero-energy photons emitted through bremsstrahlung.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The diagram in Figure 2 shows one of the several one-loop contributions to electron–electron scattering in QED.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The electron on the left side of the diagram, represented by the solid line, starts out with 4-momentum *pμ* and ends up with 4-momentum *rμ*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] It emits a virtual photon carrying *rμ* − *pμ* to transfer energy and momentum to the other electron (the black curved line).
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] But in this diagram, before that happens, it emits another virtual photon carrying 4-momentum *qμ*, which is reabsorbed after emitting the first virtual photon.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Energy and momentum conservation do not determine the 4-momentum *qμ* uniquely, so all possibilities contribute equally and we must integrate.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Here e is the electric coupling constant, and i is the imaginary unit.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Key here is the dependence on *qμ* of the three fractional factors in the integrand, which are from the propagators of the two electron lines and the photon line in the loop.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The solution to the problem of divergences was to account for the fact that initial values of quantities like the electron's electric charge and mass did not actually correspond to the physical constants measured in the laboratory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] As written, the theory was using bare particles that did not take into account the contribution of virtual-particle loop effects to the physical constants themselves.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] In general, these effects would be just as divergent as the amplitudes under consideration in the first place, so finite measured quantities would imply divergent bare quantities.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] To connect these bare values to the experimental results, the formulae would have to be rewritten in terms of measurable, renormalized quantities.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The charge of the electron, for example, could be defined in terms of a quantity measured at a specific kinematic renormalization point or subtraction point (which will have a characteristic energy, called the renormalization energy scale).
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The remaining terms left over, involving the remaining portions of the bare quantities, could then be reinterpreted as counterterms involved in a new set of diagrams exactly canceling out the earlier set of divergent diagrams.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] For example, in the Lagrangian of QED ${\mathcal {L}}={\bar {\psi }}_{B}\left[i\gamma _{\mu }\left(\partial ^{\mu }+ie_{B}A_{B}^{\mu }\right)-m_{B}\right]\psi _{B}-{\frac {1}{4}}F_{B\mu \nu }F_{B}^{\mu \nu }$ the fields and coupling constant are really bare quantities, hence the subscript B above.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] If the theory is renormalizable as in QED, the divergent parts of loop diagrams can all be decomposed into pieces with three or fewer legs, with an algebraic form that can be canceled out by the second term (or by the similar counterterms that come from *Z*0 and *Z*3).
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The diagram with the *Z*1 counterterm's interaction vertex placed as in Figure 3 cancels out the divergence from the loop in Figure 2.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Historically, the splitting of the "bare terms" into the original terms and counterterms came before the renormalization group insight due to Kenneth Wilson.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] According to such renormalization group insights, this splitting is unphysical, as all scales of the problem enter in continuous systematic ways.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] To minimize the contribution of loop diagrams to a given calculation (and therefore make it easier to extract results), one chooses a renormalization point close to the energies and momenta exchanged in the interaction.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] However, the renormalization point is not itself a physical quantity: the physical predictions of the theory, calculated to all orders, should in principle be *independent* of the choice of renormalization point, as long as it is within the domain of application of the theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Changes in renormalization scale will simply affect how much of a result comes from Feynman diagrams without loops, and how much comes from the remaining finite parts of loop diagrams.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] One can exploit this fact to calculate the effective variation of physical constants with changes in scale.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This variation is encoded by beta-functions, and the general theory of this kind of scale-dependence is known as the renormalization group.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Colloquially, particle physicists often speak of certain physical "constants" as varying with the energy of interaction, though in fact, it is the renormalization scale that is the independent quantity.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This *running* does, however, provide a convenient means of describing changes in the behavior of a field theory under changes in the energies involved in an interaction.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] For example, since the coupling in quantum chromodynamics becomes small at large energy scales, the theory behaves more like a free theory as the energy exchanged in an interaction becomes large – a phenomenon known as asymptotic freedom.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Choosing an increasing energy scale and using the renormalization group makes this clear from simple Feynman diagrams; were this not done, the prediction would be the same, but would arise from complicated high-order cancellations.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] To eliminate the divergence, simply change lower limit of integral into εa and εb: $I=\ln a-\ln b-\ln {\varepsilon _{a}}+\ln {\varepsilon _{b}}=\ln {\tfrac {a}{b}}-\ln {\tfrac {\varepsilon _{a}}{\varepsilon _{b}}}$ Making sure ⁠*εb*/*εa*⁠ → 1, then *I* = ln ⁠*a*/*b*⁠.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Since the quantity ∞ − ∞ is ill-defined, the cancelling of divergences can be made mathematically rigorous using the theory of limits, in a process known as regularization.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Integrals can be made to converge at high momenta and energy by introducing an additional modification to their form known as a regulator.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] A regulator has a characteristic energy scale known as the cutoff; taking this cutoff to infinity (or, equivalently, the corresponding length/time scale to zero) recovers the original integrals.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Divergent terms in the integrals then become finite but cutoff-dependent, which can be canceled out with cutoff-dependent counterterms.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The cutoff is taken to infinity and finite physical results are recovered; if physics on measurable scales is independent of what happens at the very short distance and time scales, then it should be possible to get cutoff-independent results.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Many different types of regulator are used in quantum field theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] One of the most popular is dimensional regularization, in which integrals are extended into a space with a fictitious fractional number of dimensions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Another is Pauli–Villars regularization, which adds fictitious particles with very large masses to the theory, such that loop integrands involving the massive particles cancel out the existing loops at large momenta.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Yet another regularization scheme is the lattice regularization, which places four-dimensional spacetime on a lattice with a fixed grid size; this size constrains the momentum that a particle can possess when propagating on the lattice.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] After treating several lattices with different grid size, the physical result is extrapolated to grid size zero i.e. the continuum limit, producing the physics of the natural universe.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The early formulators of QED and other quantum field theories were, as a rule, dissatisfied with this state of affairs.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] It seemed illegitimate to do something tantamount to subtracting infinities from infinities to get finite answers.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Dyson argued that these infinities are of a basic nature and cannot be eliminated by any formal mathematical procedures, such as the renormalization method.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Dirac's criticism was the most persistent.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Feynman was concerned that all field theories known in the 1960s had the property that the interactions become infinitely strong at short enough distance scales.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] These Landau poles made it plausible that quantum field theories were all inconsistent.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] In 1974, David Gross, Hugh David Politzer and Frank Wilczek showed that another quantum field theory, quantum chromodynamics, does not have a Landau pole.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Feynman, along with most others, accepted that quantum chromodynamics was a fully consistent theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The general unease was almost universal in texts up to the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Beginning in the 1970s, however, inspired by work on the renormalization group and effective field theory, and despite the fact that Dirac and various others never withdrew their criticisms, attitudes began to change.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Wilson and others demonstrated that the renormalization group is useful in statistical field theory applied to condensed matter physics, where it provides important insights into the behavior of phase transitions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] In condensed matter physics, a physical short-distance regulator exists: matter ceases to be continuous on the scale of atoms.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Short-distance divergences in condensed matter physics do not present a philosophical problem since the field theory is only an effective, smoothed-out representation of the behavior of matter; there are no infinities since the cutoff is always finite, and the bare quantities are cutoff-dependent.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] If quantum field theory holds past the Planck length, then there may be no problem with short-distance divergences in particle physics either, and all field theories could simply be effective field theories.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] In quantum field theory, the value of a physical constant depends on the scale that one chooses as the renormalization point.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] At energy scale of 1015 GeV (far beyond the reach of current particle accelerators), they all become approximately the same size, a major motivation for speculations about grand unified theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] If a renormalized theory can only be interpreted as an effective field theory, then the problem remains of discovering a more accurate theory that does not have these renormalization problems.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] As Lewis Ryder has put it, "In the Quantum Theory, these [classical] divergences do not disappear; on the contrary, they appear to get worse.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Not all theories lend themselves to renormalization in the manner described above, with a finite supply of counterterms and all quantities becoming cutoff-independent at the end of the calculation.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] If the Lagrangian contains combinations of field operators of high enough dimension in energy units, an infinite number of counterterms is required to cancel all divergences.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] At first glance, the theory would seem to gain an infinite number of free parameters and therefore lose all predictive power.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Such theories are called "nonrenormalizable".
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] However, in an effective field theory, "renormalizability" is a misnomer.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] In nonrenormalizable effective field theory, terms in the Lagrangian do multiply to infinity, but have coefficients suppressed by ever-increasing inverse powers of the energy cutoff.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] If the cutoff is a physical quantity—that is, if the theory is only an effective description of physics up to some maximum energy or minimum distance scale—then these additional terms could represent real physical interactions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Assuming that the dimensionless constants in the theory do not get too large, one can group calculations by inverse powers of the cutoff, and extract approximate predictions to finite order in the cutoff that still have a finite number of free parameters.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This can be used to renormalize these "nonrenormalizable" interactions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Nonrenormalizable interactions in effective field theories rapidly become weaker as the energy scale becomes much smaller than the cutoff.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] The classic example is the Fermi theory of the weak nuclear force, a nonrenormalizable effective theory whose cutoff is comparable to the mass of the W particle.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This fact may also provide a possible explanation for why almost all of the particle interactions we see are describable by renormalizable theories: others that may exist at the GUT or Planck scale simply become too weak to be observable.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] There is one exception: gravity, the exceedingly weak interaction of which is magnified by the presence of the enormous masses of stars and planets.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] A deeper understanding of the physical meaning and generalization of the renormalization process, which goes beyond the dilatation group of conventional renormalizable theories, came from condensed matter physics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Kadanoff's proposed the "block-spin" renormalization group, which defines the components of the theory at large distances as aggregates of components at shorter distances.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] This approach covered the conceptual point and was given full computational substance by Kenneth Wilson.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] In more technical terms, consider a theory described by a certain function Z of the state variables $\{s_{i}\}$ and coupling constants $\{J_{k}\}$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Z may be a partition function, an action, a Hamiltonian, etc - it must contain the whole description of the physics of the system.
[src:quantum-field-theory/renormalization] Consider a blocking transformation of the state variables $\{s_{i}\}\to \{{\tilde {s}}_{i}\}$ , where the number of ${\tilde {s}}_{i}$ must be lower than the number of $s_{i}$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The starting point of the second quantization formalism is the notion of indistinguishability of particles in quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] This implies that the quantum many-body wave function must be invariant (up to a phase factor) under the exchange of two particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] This exchange symmetry property imposes a constraint on the many-body wave function.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Each time a particle is added or removed from the many-body system, the wave function must be properly symmetrized or anti-symmetrized to satisfy the symmetry constraint.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] In the first quantization formalism, this constraint is guaranteed by representing the wave function as linear combination of permanents (for bosons) or determinants (for fermions) of single-particle states.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] In the second quantization formalism, the issue of symmetrization is automatically taken care of by the creation and annihilation operators, such that its notation can be much simpler.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Consider a complete set of single-particle wave functions $\psi _{\alpha }(\mathbf {r} )$ labeled by $\alpha$ (which may be a combined index of a number of quantum numbers).
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] represents an *N*-particle state with the *i*-th particle occupying the single-particle state $|{\alpha _{i}}\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] In the shorthanded notation, the position argument of the wave function may be omitted, and it is assumed that the *i*-th single-particle wave function describes the state of the *i*-th particle.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The wave function $\Psi$ has not been symmetrized or anti-symmetrized, thus in general not qualified as a many-body wave function for identical particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] However, it can be brought to the symmetrized (anti-symmetrized) form by operators ${\mathcal {S}}$ for symmetrizer, and ${\mathcal {A}}$ for antisymmetrizer.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] First quantized wave functions involve complicated symmetrization procedures to describe physically realizable many-body states because the language of first quantization is redundant for indistinguishable particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] In the first quantization language, the many-body state is described by answering a series of questions like *"Which particle is in which state?"*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] However these are not physical questions, because the particles are identical, and it is impossible to tell which particle is which in the first place.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The seemingly different states $\psi _{1}\otimes \psi _{2}$ and $\psi _{2}\otimes \psi _{1}$ are actually redundant names of the same quantum many-body state.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] So the symmetrization (or anti-symmetrization) must be introduced to eliminate this redundancy in the first quantization description.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] In the second quantization language, instead of asking "each particle on which state", one asks *"How many particles are there in each state?"*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Because this description does not refer to the labeling of particles, it contains no redundant information, and hence leads to a precise and simpler description of the quantum many-body state.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] meaning that there are $n_{\alpha }$ particles in the single-particle state $|\alpha \rangle$ (or as $\psi _{\alpha }$ ).
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The occupation numbers sum to the total number of particles, i.e. ${\textstyle \sum _{\alpha }n_{\alpha }=N}$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The occupation number states $|[n_{\alpha }]\rangle$ are also known as Fock states.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] All the Fock states form a complete basis of the many-body Hilbert space, or Fock space.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Any generic quantum many-body state can be expressed as a linear combination of Fock states.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Note that besides providing a more efficient language, Fock space allows for a variable number of particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] As a Hilbert space, it is isomorphic to the sum of the *n*-particle bosonic or fermionic tensor spaces described in the previous section, including a one-dimensional zero-particle space **C**.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The Fock state with all occupation numbers equal to zero is called the vacuum state, denoted $|0\rangle \equiv |\cdots ,0_{\alpha },\cdots \rangle$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The Fock state with only one non-zero occupation number is a single-mode Fock state, denoted $|n_{\alpha }\rangle \equiv |\cdots ,0,n_{\alpha },0,\cdots \rangle$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] In terms of the first quantized wave function, the vacuum state is the unit tensor product and can be denoted $|0\rangle =1$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The single-particle state is reduced to its wave function $|1_{\alpha }\rangle =\psi _{\alpha }$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Other single-mode many-body (boson) states are just the tensor product of the wave function of that mode, such as $|2_{\alpha }\rangle =\psi _{\alpha }\otimes \psi _{\alpha }$ and $|n_{\alpha }\rangle =\psi _{\alpha }^{\otimes n}$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] In general, the normalization is found to be ${\textstyle {\sqrt {\frac {1}{N!{\prod _{\alpha }{n_{\alpha }!}}}}}}$ , where *N* is the total number of particles.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] For fermion, this expression reduces to ${\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {N!}}}$ as $n_{\alpha }$ can only be either zero or one.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Note that for fermions, $n_{\alpha }=0,1$ only, so the tensor product above is effectively just a product over all occupied single-particle states.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The creation and annihilation operators are introduced to add or remove a particle from the many-body system.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] These operators lie at the core of the second quantization formalism, bridging the gap between the first- and the second-quantized states.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Applying the creation (annihilation) operator to a first-quantized many-body wave function will insert (delete) a single-particle state from the wave function in a symmetrized way depending on the particle statistics.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] On the other hand, all the second-quantized Fock states can be constructed by applying the creation operators to the vacuum state repeatedly.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The creation and annihilation operators (for bosons) are originally constructed in the context of the quantum harmonic oscillator as the raising and lowering operators, which are then generalized to the field operators in the quantum field theory.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] They are fundamental to the quantum many-body theory, in the sense that every many-body operator (including the Hamiltonian of the many-body system and all the physical observables) can be expressed in terms of them.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The creation and annihilation of a particle is implemented by the insertion and deletion of the single-particle state from the first quantized wave function in an either symmetric or anti-symmetric manner.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Here $\delta _{\alpha \beta }$ is the Kronecker delta symbol, which gives 1 if $\alpha =\beta$ , and 0 otherwise.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The subscript $\pm$ of the insertion or deletion operators indicates whether symmetrization (for bosons) or anti-symmetrization (for fermions) is implemented.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The boson creation (resp. annihilation) operator is usually denoted as $b_{\alpha }^{\dagger }$ (resp. $b_{\alpha }$ ).
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The creation operator $b_{\alpha }^{\dagger }$ adds a boson to the single-particle state $|\alpha \rangle$ , and the annihilation operator $b_{\alpha }$ removes a boson from the single-particle state $|\alpha \rangle$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The creation and annihilation operators are Hermitian conjugate to each other, but neither of them are Hermitian operators ( $b_{\alpha }\neq b_{\alpha }^{\dagger }$ ).
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] where $\psi _{\alpha }\otimes _{+}$ inserts the single-particle state $\psi _{\alpha }$ in $N+1$ possible insertion positions symmetrically, and $\psi _{\alpha }\oslash _{+}$ deletes the single-particle state $\psi _{\alpha }$ from N possible deletion positions symmetrically.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Hereinafter the tensor symbol $\otimes$ between single-particle states is omitted for simplicity.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The creation operator raises the boson occupation number by 1.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] It will also quench the vacuum state $b_{\alpha }|0_{\alpha }\rangle =0$ as there has been no boson left in the vacuum state to be annihilated.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] meaning that ${\hat {n}}_{\alpha }=b_{\alpha }^{\dagger }b_{\alpha }$ defines the boson number operator.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The above result can be generalized to any Fock state of bosons.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] These two equations can be considered as the defining properties of boson creation and annihilation operators in the second-quantization formalism.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] These commutation relations can be considered as the algebraic definition of the boson creation and annihilation operators.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The fact that the boson many-body wave function is symmetric under particle exchange is also manifested by the commutation of the boson operators.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The raising and lowering operators of the quantum harmonic oscillator also satisfy the same set of commutation relations, implying that the bosons can be interpreted as the energy quanta (phonons) of an oscillator.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] This idea is generalized in the quantum field theory, which considers each mode of the matter field as an oscillator subject to quantum fluctuations, and the bosons are treated as the excitations (or energy quanta) of the field.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The fermion creation (annihilation) operator is usually denoted as $c_{\alpha }^{\dagger }$ ( $c_{\alpha }$ ).
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The creation operator $c_{\alpha }^{\dagger }$ adds a fermion to the single-particle state $|\alpha \rangle$ , and the annihilation operator $c_{\alpha }$ removes a fermion from the single-particle state $|\alpha \rangle$ .
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] where $\psi _{\alpha }\otimes _{-}$ inserts the single-particle state $\psi _{\alpha }$ in $N+1$ possible insertion positions anti-symmetrically, and $\psi _{\alpha }\oslash _{-}$ deletes the single-particle state $\psi _{\alpha }$ from N possible deletion positions anti-symmetrically.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] It is particularly instructive to view the results of creation and annihilation operators on states of two (or more) fermions, because they demonstrate the effects of exchange.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] A few illustrative operations are given in the example below.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The complete algebra for creation and annihilation operators on a two-fermion state can be found in *Quantum Photonics*.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The minus sign (known as the fermion sign) appears due to the anti-symmetric property of the fermion wave function.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] If the single-particle state $|\alpha \rangle$ is empty, the creation operator will fill the state with a fermion.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] However, if the state is already occupied by a fermion, further application of the creation operator will quench the state, demonstrating the Pauli exclusion principle that two identical fermions can not occupy the same state simultaneously.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The vacuum state is quenched by the action of the annihilation operator.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] meaning that ${\hat {n}}_{\alpha }=c_{\alpha }^{\dagger }c_{\alpha }$ defines the fermion number operator.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The above result can be generalized to any Fock state of fermions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Recall that the occupation number $n_{\alpha }$ can only take 0 or 1 for fermions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] These two equations can be considered as the defining properties of fermion creation and annihilation operators in the second quantization formalism.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] This observation leads to the idea that fermions are emergent particles in the long-range entangled local qubit system.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] These anti-commutation relations can be considered as the algebraic definition of the fermion creation and annihilation operators.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The fact that the fermion many-body wave function is anti-symmetric under particle exchange is also manifested by the anti-commutation of the fermion operators.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The creation and annihilation operators are Hermitian conjugate to each other, but neither of them are Hermitian operators ( $c_{\alpha }\neq c_{\alpha }^{\dagger }$ ).
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] They can be viewed as the fermionic analog of position and momentum operators of a "fermionic" Harmonic oscillator.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] where $i,j$ labels any Majorana fermion operators on equal footing (regardless their origin from Re or Im combination of complex fermion operators $c_{\alpha }$ ).
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The anticommutation relation indicates that Majorana fermion operators generates a Clifford algebra, which can be systematically represented as Pauli operators in the many-body Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] These are second quantization operators, with coefficients $\psi _{\nu }\left(\mathbf {r} \right)$ and $\psi _{\nu }^{*}\left(\mathbf {r} \right)$ that are ordinary first-quantization wavefunctions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Thus, for example, any expectation values will be ordinary first-quantization wavefunctions.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Loosely speaking, $\Psi ^{\dagger }(\mathbf {r} )$ is the sum of all possible ways to add a particle to the system at position **r** through any of the basis states $\psi _{\nu }\left(\mathbf {r} \right)$ , not necessarily plane waves, as below.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] Since $\Psi (\mathbf {r} )$ and $\Psi ^{\dagger }(\mathbf {r} )$ are second quantization operators defined in every point in space they are called quantum field operators.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] The term "second quantization", introduced by Jordan, is a misnomer that has persisted for historical reasons.
[src:quantum-field-theory/second-quantization] One is merely quantizing each oscillator in this assembly, shifting from a semiclassical treatment of the system to a fully quantum-mechanical one.
